# nutanix_vm — Terraform Module

## Description

This module provisions virtual machines on Nutanix AHV via Prism Central.
It supports two provisioning paths controlled by the `source_type` variable:
`"template"` deploys a VM from a Prism Central VM Template using the
`nutanix_deploy_templates_v2` resource, while `"image"` clones from an Image
Service image using `nutanix_virtual_machine`. Both paths share a common
variable interface. The module enforces all 10 mandatory Nutanix categories
defined in the Umicore HLD as required inputs, builds a consistent VM name
from the site code, usage code, and sequence number, and supports optional
guest customisation via Sysprep (Windows) or cloud-init (Linux).

---

## Usage

### Template path — Windows Server

```hcl
module "app_server" {
  source = "./nutanix_vm"

  UMICORE_LOCATION = "HOB"
  UMICORE_PROJECT  = "NUTANIXPRD"
  environment      = "prd"

  usage_code           = "AS"
  sequence_number      = 1
  source_type          = "template"
  template_name        = "WIN2025-golden-v1.0"
  cluster_name         = "HOB-NTX-CL01"
  subnet_name          = "VLAN-APP-100"
  num_vcpus_per_socket = 4
  num_cpu_sockets      = 1
  memory_size_mib      = 8192
  os_type              = "windows"

  sysprep_xml = file("${path.module}/sysprep/unattend.xml")

  category_business_unit    = "Manufacturing"
  category_environment      = "prd"
  category_criticality      = "High"
  category_recharge         = "CC-MFG-001"
  category_primary_function = "ApplicationServer"
  category_application      = "SAP"
  category_description      = "HOB plant application server"
  category_bu_responsible   = "plant-owner@umicore.com"
  category_it_responsible   = "infra-team@umicore.com"
  category_backup           = "Gold"
}
```

### Image path — Linux / appliance

```hcl
module "db_server" {
  source = "./nutanix_vm"

  UMICORE_LOCATION = "HOB"
  UMICORE_PROJECT  = "NUTANIXPRD"
  environment      = "prd"

  usage_code           = "DB"
  sequence_number      = 1
  source_type          = "image"
  image_name           = "RHEL9-golden-v1.0"
  cluster_name         = "HOB-NTX-CL01"
  subnet_name          = "VLAN-DB-200"
  num_vcpus_per_socket = 4
  num_cpu_sockets      = 2
  memory_size_mib      = 16384
  os_disk_size_gib     = 80
  os_type              = "linux"

  data_disks = [
    { size_gib = 500, label = "data" },
    { size_gib = 200, label = "logs" },
  ]

  cloud_init_userdata = file("${path.module}/cloud-init/db.yaml")

  category_business_unit    = "IT"
  category_environment      = "prd"
  category_criticality      = "High"
  category_recharge         = "CC-IT-DB"
  category_primary_function = "Database"
  category_application      = "PostgreSQL"
  category_description      = "HOB primary database server"
  category_bu_responsible   = "dba-team@umicore.com"
  category_it_responsible   = "infra-team@umicore.com"
  category_backup           = "Gold"
}
```

---

## Naming Convention

When `vm_name_override` is not set the module computes the VM name as:

```
<UMICORE_LOCATION>-<usage_code>-<NNNN>
```

All components are lowercased and the sequence number is zero-padded to four
digits (e.g. `hob-as-0001`). The resulting name is at most 10 characters,
which fits safely within the 15-character Windows NetBIOS hostname limit.

For acquired or migrated servers that must keep an existing hostname, set
`vm_name_override` to the legacy name. The override is used verbatim — no
lowercasing or site-code prefix is applied — so the caller is responsible for
ensuring the value is a valid hostname for the target OS.

---

## Requirements

| Component | Version |
|---|---|
| Terraform | >= 1.8 |
| nutanix/nutanix provider | ~> 2.4 |
| Nutanix AOS | >= 7.5 |
| Prism Central | >= 7.5 |

